--------------------
file: /cmds/mortal/changelog.c
  ::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::keywords: changelog, changes
aliases:
short: Changelog
header: View Changelog Entries

  SYNTAX:  changelog [categories | [all|new] [category]]

Lists all changelog entries in reverse order so newest entries are
first. If neither [all] or [new] are passed as arguments, the most
recent 5 entries are shown.

Optional Arguments:
[categories] - Lists all optional categories.

[all] - Lists all entries regardless of age.
[new] - Lists only the newest entry.
        Mutually exclusive, only one or the other can be used.

[category] - Lists only changes that fall under the desired category.
             Can be combined with [all] or [new].

This list will not be all inclusive and exhaustive, nor will it
include changes that are documented elsewhere, such as guild,
crafting, profession, or other places where files like 'info new'
already exist for tracking such changes.

Whether something is added to this list is up to the discretion
of the wizard management.
--------------------
file: /cmds/mortal/chatlines.c
keywords: mortal, communication, mudansi
aliases:chatline
short: Your available chatlines
header: Topic:  Chatlines

  SYNTAX:  chatlines

The 'chatlines' command will allow you to see a list of all
of the chatlines to which you have access.  It will list the
name of the chatline, the ansi variable that may be set using
mud ansi, the number of people currently using that chatline, the
default # of history lines accessed, and the command required
to use that chatline.

Each chatline can be accessed with the command word shown in the
list when you type 'chatlines'.  Each of these, in turn, allows
some options.  For example, if you had the 'newbie' chatline
available with 'newbie' as a command word, you could do the
following:

     newbie <message>          Send a message on this chatline
     newbie -?                 Show all of the chatline's options
     newbie -h                 Show this line's default history
     newbie -h <#>             Show <#> lines of line's history
     newbie -w                 List the people on this line
     newbie -b                 Toggle on/off line blocking
     newbie -ab                Toggle on/off announcement blocking
     newbie -cc                Loop through line options (client only)

Please do not send ANSI escape codes to chatlines.


--------------------
file: /cmds/mortal/cheatwho.c
keywords: mortal, botcheck
aliases: 
short: Find players that are cheating
header: Topic:  Cheatwho
syntax: cheatwho

Using a complex set of heuristics and cutting edge algorithms derived in
part from antivirus scanning software and some code supplied by a Google
employee, cheatwho analyzes command patterns and frequencies to deduce
which currently logged in player is most likely cheating. While no
automated system can ever be perfectly accurate, testing has shown cheatwho
to be very reliable in assessing a likely target, which then could be 
followed up with a botcheck of the suspect.

