file: /cmds/mortal/kickstart.c
keywords: mortal, bug, reporting
aliases: 
short: Initiate a Code-Blue
header: Command: kickstart

   Syntax:	kickstart

If for some reason your heart stops beating, this command will
get out the electro-shock paddles and get your ticker going again.


--------------------
file: /cmds/mortal/kill.c
keywords: mortal, kills, combat, wimpy, anarchy, pk, bloodmatch, killed
aliases: 
short: Start attacking something/someone
header: Command: Kill

   Syntax:	kill <who|what>

Yes, here it is.  This is what the mud is all about.  Senseless
killing.  This command will initiate combat (for better or for worse)
between you and the named critter or player.

NOTE:  You will only be able to initiate combat with another player
  if you are both PK (player killers) and satisfy a number of requirements
  regarding levels and such (see 'help pk'), during an Anarchy (help
  anarchy), or during a Bloodmatch (help bloodmatch).

   Example

>kill bandersnatch
You attack the frumious bandersnatch.


--------------------
file: /cmds/mortal/killed.c
keywords: mortal, combat, kill, kills
aliases: 
short:  What have you killed so far?
header: Command: Killed

  Syntax:  killed [<count>] | [top [<count>]] | [last [<count>]]

 killed [<count>]      Shows up to the top <count> and last <count>
                       monsters you killed.
 killed top [<count>]  Shows up to the top <count> monsters you killed.
 killed last [<count>] Shows up to the last <count> monsters you
                       killed.

If <count> is not specified, it defaults to 20. If <count> is greater
than 20 only 20 will be shown. If you have less than <count> or 20 kills,
all your kills will be shown.


--------------------
file: /cmds/mortal/kills.c
keywords: mortal, combat, kill, killed
aliases: 
short:  How many kills do you have this login?
header: Command: Kills

  Syntax:  kills

Reports the total number of kills and unique kills (up to 5000) that
you've accomplished in the current login.

A unique kill generally involves monsters with different names or short
descriptions, and generally also not produced from random creature
generators such as challenge arenas and virtual areas.


--------------------
file: /cmds/mortal/ktrig.c
keywords: mortal, basic, corpse
aliases: 
short: Set a kill trigger
header: Command: Ktrig

   Syntax:	ktrig <commands>

Usage of this command requires the 'ktrig1' vaf perk ('vaf ktrig1' for more)

This command allows you to set an action or set of actions to fire
when you kill the monster you are fighting.  Actions are separated by
a forward slash and you can have up to 3 with the 'ktrig1' vaf or 10 if
you also have the 'ktrig2' vaf perk.  In addition, you can use the
special character '$' in place of the corpse name itself so that you
are specifically targetting the corpse you just created (if any) by
killing this monster.

The ktrig of the player tanking is called first followed by the ktrig
of the player that got the killing blow (if different.)  You can change
when you want yours to fire by toggling off TANK or KBLOW if, for example,
you don't want your ktrig to fire on monsters you're not tanking.

Other options:  CLEAR, ON, OFF, TANK (toggles), KBLOW (toggles)
See also     :  (in a party) phelp ktrig

   Example

>ktrig get corpse/put corpse in bag
Gets the corpse (generic) and puts it in a bag.

>ktrig get $/put $ in bag
Gets the corpse of the creature you just killed and puts it in a bag.

--------------------
file: /cmds/mortal/levels.c
keywords: mortal
aliases: 
short: Required Experience Point
header: Player Levels
syntax: levels <optional # up to 144>

The levels command will show you how much experience points are required
to achieve a given player level.  The optional argument will allow you
to see the amount of experience points required to reach that level, as
well as a range around that number.


--------------------
file: /cmds/mortal/lineofsight.c
keywords: mortal, look
aliases:
short: Line of Sight
header: Command: lineofsight
Coupled with a cartography skill of 3, this command allows you to see
surrounding rooms within your current line-of-sight.  Rooms (O) are shown
in a bird's eye mapping format with corresponding exits (^ = up, v = down,
+ = up+down, E = enter) as well as any players, monsters or npcs that may
happen to be in the area (not including your current room).  Your current
room appears as @ unless it has one of the specific exits noted above,
which will appear in yellow.

Even with lower cartography skills ('help adventuring.cartography') you
are able to passively view the cardinal minimap for each room you
encounter.  To fully utilize the ability while exploring (i.e. 'look'ing
or via the passive viewing of the long description of a room) you need
to have mapping enabled in your 'brief' settings ('help brief').
Also, typing 'lineofsight brief' will manually display the minimap.

Be aware that regardless of your skill level, some areas (?) and/or creatures
will be unable to be sighted, particularly guild followers.  Additionally,
assuming you have a light source, dark rooms (#) are viewable along your
line of sight, but you will find that the further the peer into the
darkness, the more powerful of a light source you will need to have.


--------------------
file: /cmds/mortal/llook.c
keywords: mortal, basic, look, examine, exa
aliases: 
short: Look at short description of room and exits
header: Topic: Long Look

  SYNTAX:  llook

The 'glance' command shows the player the short description of the
room he or she is in, the visible exits from the room, and any
monsters, players, or objects that are in the room with them.
The long description of the room may be seen by a simple 'look'.


--------------------
file: /cmds/mortal/look.c
keywords: mortal, exa, examine, search, basic, glance, llook
aliases: 
short: How to make use of your eyes
header: Command: Look

   Syntax:   look at [what] <on ground | in room>
        or:   look

The look command allows you to examine your
environment.  The plain version 'look' gives
you a description of the room you are in.
You can specify 'on ground' if you are trying to look at an object
lying on the ground, such as a sword or monster.  This is useful if
there is a conflicting item in the room you can also look at.
You can specify 'in room' if you are trying to look at something that
is part of the room description and there's a conflicting item on the
ground.

With 'look at something', you can scrutinize
something more closely.

   Example

look at paper
look at sword 2
look at paper in room
look at paper on ground
look at potion 3 on ground


